54.	As discussed below, I believe that Mr. Isaacman did intend to misappropriate Card Connect’s trade secrets. For example, I note that the project to acquire Card Connect was given the code name “Project Lightning,” and I find use of that term to describe the project and what allegedly occurred as a result of the letter to be interesting. Mr. Isaacman has an interest in numerology and a concept called “Gematria,” which involves, in part, assigning numbers to letters. From my review of various materials, I saw some of the communications and notes from others with Shift4 referencing “Lightning Strikes,” (Ex. 66, Bates CC-SHF0006111) and “Lightning Strikes Again” (Ex. 69 Bates CC-SF00007297). Mr. Isaacman explained that he approved the name because:

Mr. Isaacman has testified that he “was looking for words that scored ideally either 74 or 47. 74 because that is where Shift4 derives from, because we do payments, we do 24/7, and Lightning adds to 47. (Isaacman Dep. 59:1-20.) Mr. Isaacman further testified that “strikes” adds to 74. “So Lightning Strikes without project would equal 121 which adds to a four.” (Id. at 60.) Mr. Isaacman also agreed that he was the one who “approved” “the ultimate name” for the deal. (Id. at 59.)
